Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization with exposed area of 1 cm2. Potentiodynamic polarization experiments were carried out using a scan rate of 0.1 mV/s commencing at a potential about 250 mV more active than the stable OCP. Before starting the polarization scan, the specimen in the sample holder (WE) was left in the cell for about 1 h to attain a steady state which is shown by a constant potential and current at the beginning of the experiment. The potcntiodynamic runs were programmed such that upon attaining a current density of 25에/cm^2, the scan direction was reversed and the potentials were scanned back to the starting potential.

Heat treatment: Ingots were cast and hot rolled to 20 mm diameter bars which were heat treated at ll00싺 for 30 min and cooled in still air
Comments: The specimen surface was ground to a 120 grit finish and 5 cm2 was exposed to the corrodent.

Test Method: Polarization curves were obtained potentiodynamically at a scan rate of 20 mV/min, using a Tacussel electrochemical set composed of a potentiostat, a current recorder, and a high impedance electronic millivoltmeter.
Heat treatment: Solution treatment was performed by heating in nitrogen at 1150 C for 30 minutes followed by water quenching.
Comments: The temperature was not specified for this experiment, but was explicitely shown as 60 oC for parallel experiments. For electrochemical measurement, the surfaces studied were mechanically polished with emery paper under water up to grade 1000, then were degreased in absolute ethyl alcohol, washed in deionized water, and dried by warm air blowing.

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization. The potential was controlled by a Wenkingt potentiostat (Model 68 TS-3) and changed in steps of 10 mV with a Wenking SMP 69 scanning potentiometer every hour for the positive polarization direction until the onset of pitting or appearance of pits, and every 100 s for the reverse scan until zero current. The potential was initially held at 150 mV for 1 h to attain stable current, whereupon the scanning potentiometer was activated.

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization. Potentiodynamic sweeps in hot 3.5% NaCl solution were carried out at a rate of 1 mV s-1. The tests were carried out in a glass three-electrode cell held in a water bath at 65 C. In all experiments the rod under test was supported in a holder on the lid of the cell such that the end face just touched the surface of the test solution as described above. The counter electrode was a platinum wire, the reference electrode a saturated calomel electrode (SCE) at the same solution temperature; all potentials are given against the SCE. The potential at which the current density exceeded 50 uA cm-2 was defined as the pitting potential.
Heat treatment: annealled at 1020C for 2h, then water quenched

Heat treatment: 0.25 um diamond finish, annealed at 1100C for 3h and water quenched

Test Method: Potentiostatic Polarization, Potentiostatic polarization curves were obtained at 25C and at 0C in N,-saturated 0.1N NaCl and O*lN NaBr. The electrode totally immersed was first polarized in the least noble passive region for 15min, then the potential was moved in the noble direction 50mV every Smin until the pitting potential was approximated and the current showed a marked increase. This was followed by longer-time runs of 12-15h at a single potential in the neighbourhood of the critical potential in order to establish the steady state value. The least noble potential at which the current did not continuously increase with time and at which no pits could be observed under a low power microscope was taken as the final value.
Heat treatment: Alloys were prepared by vacuum melting in dense alumina crucibles decarburized electrolytic Fe, electrolytic Cr and carbonyl Ni, the latter supplied by courtesy of the International Nickel Company. Re containing 15 ppm Fe but less than I ppm of any other detectable impurity was supplied by courtesy of Ledgemont Laboratory,Kennecott Copper Corporation. The melt was cast in a purified argon atmosphere by drawing into 7mm dia. Vycor tubes and quenching in water. The alloys were homogenized at 1050C for 17h, swaged to 0.4cm diameter rods, annealed at 1050C and water quenched.
Comments: The electrode totally immersed was first polarized in the least noble passive region for 15min, then the potential was moved in the noble direction 50mV every 5min until the pitting potential was approximated and the current showed a marked increase.

The alloys were homogenized at 1050C for 17h, swaged to 0.4cm diameter rods, annealed at 1050C and water quenched.
Comments: The electrode totally immersed was first polarized in the least noble passive region for 15min, then the potential was moved in the noble direction 50mV every 5min until the pitting potential was approximated and the current showed a marked increase.

Test Method: Polarization test, strips of 1.25 cm x 1.25 cm of the experimental alloys, as well as the commercial alloys, were subjected to anodic polarization in dearated 1 N NaCI solution at 30 C. A Type 308 rod was welded to one side of each specimen and covered with rubber tubing, except the tip for electrical connection to a potentiostat. The specimens were then mounted in epoxy, ground to 600 grit, and rinsed with distilled water. The specimen/mount interface was covered with a thin film of lacquer, and approximately 1 cm 2 of the specimen was exposed. They were then kept in a desiccator until testing. The testing procedure consisted of: (1) introduction of the solution to a one liter polarization cell; (2) setting the temperature of the solution; (3) deoxygenating the solution with prepurified nitrogen at the rate of 90 ml/min starting 30 minutes before immersion of the specimen; (4) cleaning the specimen with distilled water just prior to transferring to the cel]; and (5) anodic polarization 50 minutes after the immersion at a scanning rate of 20 mV/min, using a PAR Model 173 potentiostat and ELSCINT Model ABA-26 Automatic Baseline Advance.
Heat treatment: The stainless steels evaluated in this study were prepared from commercially pure grades of Fe, Ni, ferrochrome, Mn, Mo, Si, manganese or chromium nitride, and chromium carbide. Melting was done in a vacuum induction furnace.The melting procedure consisted of: (1) melting Fe, Ni, Mo, Mn, and ferrochrome in a vacuum; (2) bleeding nitrogen into the furnace; and (3) introducing Mn4N or CrN, wrapped in iron foil, into the melt, as needed. After casting, only solid sections of the ingots were taken to prepare test specimens. The sections were first soaked for 30 minutes and hot rolled. The temperatures were 1205 C and 1095 C, depending upon hot ductility of the heats. The hot rolled specimens were pickled in a solution containing 10% HNO3 and 2% HF at 65 C to remove the hot working scale, cold rolled to 2 mm, annealed at 1065 C for 5 minutes, water quenched, and pickled again in the same HNO3-HF solution at 65 C. A small section was cut from each heat and used for chemical analysis.
Microstructures: Nitrogen, which is an austenite stabilizer, shifts the a-'y phase boundaries in Fe-Cr-Ni alloys, as described in Figure 8.
Comments: Some compositions were provided with "~" and "<" signs in the paper

Test Method: Polarization test, strips of 1.25 cm x 1.25 cm of the experimental alloys, as well as the commercial alloys, were subjected to anodic polarization in dearated 1 N NaCI solution at 30 C. A Type 308 rod was welded to one side of each specimen and covered with rubber tubing, except the tip for electrical connection to a potentiostat. The specimens were then mounted in epoxy, ground to 600 grit, and rinsed with distilled water. The specimen/mount interface was covered with a thin film of lacquer, and approximately 1 cm 2 of the specimen was exposed. They were then kept in a desiccator until testing. The testing procedure consisted of: (1) introduction of the solution to a one liter polarization cell; (2) setting the temperature of the solution; (3) deoxygenating the solution with prepurified nitrogen at the rate of 90 ml/min starting 30 minutes before immersion of the specimen; (4) cleaning the specimen with distilled water just prior to transferring to the cel]; and (5) anodic polarization 50 minutes after the immersion at a scanning rate of 20 mV/min, using a PAR Model 173 potentiostat and ELSCINT Model ABA-26 Automatic Baseline Advance.
Heat treatment: The stainless steels evaluated in this study were prepared from commercially pure grades of Fe, Ni, ferrochrome, Mn, Mo, Si, manganese or chromium nitride, and chromium carbide. Melting was done in a vacuum induction furnace.The melting procedure consisted of: (1) melting Fe, Ni, Mo, Mn, and ferrochrome in a vacuum; (2) bleeding nitrogen into the furnace; and (3) introducing Mn4N or CrN, wrapped in iron foil, into the melt, as needed. After casting, only solid sections of the ingots were taken to prepare test specimens. The sections were first soaked for 30 minutes and hot rolled. Microstructures: Nitrogen, which is an austenite stabilizer, shifts the a-'y phase boundaries in Fe-Cr-Ni alloys, as described in Figure 8.
Comments: Some compositions were provided with "~" and "<" signs in the paper

Test Method: Polarization test, strips of 1.25 cm x 1.25 cm of the experimental alloys, as well as the commercial alloys, were subjected to anodic polarization in dearated 1 N NaCI solution at 30 C. A Type 308 rod was welded to one side of each specimen and covered with rubber tubing, except the tip for electrical connection to a potentiostat. The specimens were then mounted in epoxy, ground to 600 grit, and rinsed with distilled water. The specimen/mount interface was covered with a thin film of lacquer, and approximately 1 cm 2 of the specimen was exposed. They were then kept in a desiccator until testing. The testing procedure consisted of: (1) introduction of the solution to a one liter polarization cell; (2) setting the temperature of the solution; (3) deoxygenating the solution with prepurified nitrogen at the rate of 90 ml/min starting 30 minutes before immersion of the specimen; (4) cleaning the specimen with distilled water just prior to transferring to the cel]; and (5) anodic polarization 50 minutes after the immersion at a scanning rate of 20 mV/min, using a PAR Model 173 potentiostat and ELSCINT Model ABA-26 Automatic Baseline Advance.
Heat treatment: The stainless steels evaluated in this study were prepared from commercially pure grades of Fe, Ni, ferrochrome, Mn, Mo, Si, manganese or chromium nitride, and chromium carbide. Melting was done in a vacuum induction furnace.The melting procedure consisted of: (1) melting Fe, Ni, Mo, Mn, and ferrochrome in a vacuum; (2) bleeding nitrogen into the furnace; and (3) introducing Mn4N or CrN, wrapped in iron foil, into the melt, as needed. After casting, only solid sections of the ingots were taken to prepare test specimens. The sections were first soaked for 30 minutes and hot rolled. The temperatures were 1205 C and 1095 C, depending upon hot ductility of the heats. The hot rolled specimens were pickled in a solution containing 10% HNO3 and 2% HF at 65 C to remove the hot working scale, cold rolled to 2 mm, annealed at 1065 C for 5 minutes, water quenched, and pickled again in the same HNO3-HF solution at 65 C. A small section was cut from each heat and used for chemical analysis.
Microstructures: Nitrogen, which is an austenite stabilizer, shifts the a-'y phase boundaries in Fe-Cr-Ni alloys, as described in Figure 8.
Comments: Some compositions were provided with "~" and "<" signs in the paper

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization, the specimen surface was ground to a 120 grit finish and 5 cm2 was exposed to the corrodent. The potential was controlled, relative to a standard saturated calomel electrode, by a potentiostat. Following. pretreatment for 5 min at -1.5 V, the -potential was increased-rapidly to -0.5V and thereafter at a steady rate of 1V in 50 min. In this work the critical pitting potential was taken as that at which there was an anodic current flow of 10^-5 A/cm2.
Heat treatment: 5 kg melts were made at atmospheric pressure in an induction furnace using Japanese iron, nickel pellets, electrolytic chromium, ferro-molybdenum, refined manganese, and high-nitrogen ferro-chromium. Ingots were cast and hot rolled to 20 mm diameter bars which were heat treated at 1100싺 for 30 min and cooled in still air.
Comments: Pitting corrosion data is collected from plain breakdown potential in table II.

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization, the specimens were cut from rods and mounted in epoxy resin so that the exposed surface area was about 0.8 cm^2. This surface was coarse-ground with silicon-carbide papers and then fine-ground with alumina paste.
Heat treatment: Steels used for this study were kindly supplied by the Institute of Iron Metallurgy in Gliwice, Poland. They were in the form of hot forged rods, 18 mm in diameter. The steels were tested in the as-received and quenched after 1 hour of heaing in air at 1120oC
Comments: In the hot-forged condition the steels with 0.12, 0.25, and 0.35%N were austenitic, whereas those with 0.07 and 0.17% N contained austenite with a small amount of ??-ferrite (with an excess of Cr and relatively less Fe, Ni, and Mn than in the , ?? phase). Some small second-phase particles also occurred. Electron microprobe analysis identified these particles as carbides (Me23C6 type) and carbonitrides (Me23C6 type). Pure nitrides were very rare. The X-ray analysis did not detect any a-phase in the materials under investigation.

Comments: In the hot-forged condition the steels with 0.12, 0.25, and 0.35%N were austenitic, whereas those with 0.07 and 0.17% N contained austenite with a small amount of ??-ferrite (with an excess of Cr and relatively less Fe, Ni, and Mn than in the , ?? phase). Some small second-phase particles also occurred. Electron microprobe analysis identified these particles as carbides (Me23C6 type) and carbonitrides (Me23C6 type). Pure nitrides were very rare. The X-ray analysis did not detect any a-phase in the materials under investigation.

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization, the specimens were cut from rods and mounted in epoxy resin so that the exposed surface area was about 0.8 cm^2. This surface was coarse-ground with silicon-carbide papers and then fine-ground with alumina paste.
Heat treatment: Steels used for this study were kindly supplied by the Institute of Iron Metallurgy in Gliwice, Poland. They were in the form of hot forged rods, 18 mm in diameter. Quenching in water occurered after either (1) heating 1h in air at 1050C, (2) heating 0.5h in air at 1050C
Comments: In the as-received specimens of the 18Cr-5Ni-0.03Mn steel, metallographic examination revealed the presence of martensite with some inclusions of ??-ferrite. As determined by X-ray analysis, the alloys with more than 5% Mn contained austenite and ferrite. No traces of ??-phase were detected. The amount of ??-phase depended upon the steel composition.  The higher the Mn content was and the lower the C and the N contents were, the greater the amount of ??-phase present. However, heat-to-heat variations also very likely influenced the phase composition of the alloys under investigation. In all specimens, small particles of a foreign phase were detected. They were identified by electron probe analysis as carbides (presumably Me23C6).

Comments: no major difference between different sample in fig 1

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization, Cu-wire was spot-welded to one side of each specimen, mounted in epoxy resin, and ground to 2000 grade silicon carbide. To avoid crevice corrosion, the specimenmount interface was carefully coated with a thin 숇m of silicone sealant. Approximately 1 cm2 of the surface was exposed to the test solution.
Heat treatment: The alloys were induction melted in a vacuum furnace and cast into ingots. The ingots were hot-rolled in a controlled atmosphere, and then cold-rolled to 2.154 mm thick sheets. Before the experiments, all specimens were solution annealed for 20 min at 1150C, and then water quenched.
Microstructures: Single austenitic phase. No second phase. Two types of inclusions, MnS and alumina, were found

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization. Potentiodynamic polarization tests were performed using a three-electrode cell system consisting of a saturated calomel electrode (SCE) as a reference, a platinum electrode as a counter, and a specimen as the working electrode. The sample was kept immersed in the test solution for 2 h at open-circuit potential. After obtaining the stable corrosion potential (Ecorr), the potential was raised in the anodic direction, from 100 mV below Ecorr, at a scan rate of 0.2 mV/s.
Heat treatment: The alloys were induction melted in a vacuum furnace and cast into ingots. The ingots were hot-rolled in a controlled atmosphere, and then cold-rolled to 2.154 mm thick sheets. Before the experiments, all specimens were solution annealed for 20 min at 1150C, and then water quenched.
Microstructures: Single austenitic phase. No second phase. Two types of inclusions, MnS and alumina, were found

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization. Polarization was performed in an electrochemical cell attached to the ESCA instrument. The arrangement allows the samples to be transferred to the analyser without air exposure. The electrolyte was de-aerated by Ar bubbling for 2 h before exposure. The samples were activated at - 700 mV for 10 min. The sweep rate at the potentiodynamic tests was 1 mVs_. The samples prepared for the ESCA analyses were polarized by stepping the potential from the activation potential to the potentials - 75, 500 and 800 mV (SCE). The potentials were maintained for 10 min and 2 h.
Heat treatment: The steels were heat treated at 1100 and 1250C followed by quenching in water in order to homogenize the structure.
Comments: no major difference between two samples

Test Method: Potentiostatic Polarization. The experimental procedure was to first polarize the electrode potentiostatically at the least noble potential within the passive region for at least 15 min in order to achieve steady-state passivity. The potential was then advanced in stages of 50 mV, allowing 5 min between each change. Initially the current decreased or remained constant after each potential adjustment, but eventually a steadily increasing current at some potential V'c indicated the onset of pitting (or of transpassivity). Steady-state values Vc were obtained subsequently by holding the potential for long times at a fixed value and then observing pitting or the lack of it under a low power microscope. The lowest potential for which pitting could not be observed after a 10-hr or longer period of constant polarization was considered to be the steady-state value Vc. Reproducibility was in the order of 5 mv.
Heat treatment: The ingots were homogenized in A or He, usually at 1050-1100 oC for several hours. Ingots of Ni-Cr, Ni-Mo, and Cr-Fe were cold rolled to 0.25 cm, then annealed at 1000-1050 oC and water quenched. The Cr-Fe alloys containing more than 40% Cr were difficult to roll or swage, hence electrodes were machined directly from the homogenized ingot. Ingots of the lower % Cr-Fe alloys and of the stainless steels were swaged to about 0.45 cm diam rods, annealed at 1050 oC and water quenched. All electrodes measured approximately 2 cm long and were either 0.4 cm diam or 0.5 cm wide by 0.2 cm thick.
Comments: The electrodes were abraded to a final 3/0 emery paper, and pickled usually in 15% HNO3, 5% HF at 80 oC for 5 min to remove the cold worked surface.

Reproducibility was in the order of 5 mv.
Heat treatment: The ingots were homogenized in A or He, usually at 1050-1100 oC for several hours. Ingots of Ni-Cr, Ni-Mo, and Cr-Fe were cold rolled to 0.25 cm, then annealed at 1000-1050 oC and water quenched. The Cr-Fe alloys containing more than 40% Cr were difficult to roll or swage, hence electrodes were machined directly from the homogenized ingot. Ingots of the lower % Cr-Fe alloys and of the stainless steels were swaged to about 0.45 cm diam rods, annealed at 1050 oC and water quenched. All electrodes measured approximately 2 cm long and were either 0.4 cm diam or 0.5 cm wide by 0.2 cm thick.
Comments: The electrodes were abraded to a final 3/0 emery paper, and pickled usually in 15% HNO3, 5% HF at 80 oC for 5 min to remove the cold worked surface.

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization. The onset of pitting was marked by a sharp and sudden increase in polarization current. The potential scanning was stopped at the pitting potential, and the electrode was allowed to pit for 20 to 30 min. It was then removed from the solution, the tape was stripped, and its surface was examined for pitting and possible crevice corrosion. The potential scanning was usually started at -0.7 to -0.6v, with respect to the saturated calomel electrode (SCE); the scanning was always into the passive potential region. In some experiments, the potential of an actively corroding electrode was changed almost instantaneously to a selected potential in a passive range by switching on a potentiostat, with a potential preset at a desired value.
Heat treatment: Two sets of laboratory-prepared ferritic alloys and two commercial ferritic stainless steels (Types 430 and 4341) were investigated. The high-purity 17% chromium, 17% Cr-l% Mo, and 17% Cr-3% Mo laboratory alloys were prepared by melting and casting in vacuum. The resulting ingots were hot-rolled to 0.64-cmthick sheet, which was cold-rolled to a 0.32-cm thickness, annealed for 1 hr at 815~ and water-quenched. The 18% Cr-2% Mo alloys modified by titanium and Type 434 is the proposed designation for stainless steel conraining 17% chromium and 1% molybdenum. nickel additions were produced by induction melting in an argon atmosphere, using the split-heat technique. In this technique, the base composition is melted, and part of the melt is poured off to produce an ingot; then to the balance of the melt, the required alloying additions are made and the next ingot is cast. This process is repeated until a series of the desired compositions is cast. The 18% Cr-2% Mo ingots were hotforged, hot-rolled to 0.76-cm-thick strips, and coldrolled to 0.38-cm-thick strips. The 18% Cr-2% Mo alloys containing titanium were annealed for 1 hr at 104O~ the minimum temperature that prevented formation of a second phase in the high titanium alloy, and then water-quenched. The rest of the 18% Cr-2% Mo materials and the hot-rolled, commercial Types 430 and 434 steels were annealed at 815~ for 1 hr and water-quenched.
Comments: The electrodes for the potentiodynamic studies were mounted in acrylic plastic, the exposed surface (0.5 by 0.6 cm) always being a longitudinal section parallel to the rolled surface. The exposed surface was polished using standard metallographic techniques, ending with a distilled water slurry of 0.3~ alumina. For the pitting potential measurements, the electrode surface was masked with electroplaters tape (Scotch 470), except for a circular area 0.36 cm in diameter.

Heat treatment: Two sets of laboratory-prepared ferritic alloys and two commercial ferritic stainless steels (Types 430 and 4341) were investigated. The high-purity 17% chromium, 17% Cr-l% Mo, and 17% Cr-3% Mo laboratory alloys were prepared by melting and casting in vacuum. The resulting ingots were hot-rolled to 0.64-cmthick sheet, which was cold-rolled to a 0.32-cm thickness, annealed for 1 hr at 815~ and water-quenched. The 18% Cr-2% Mo alloys modified by titanium and Type 434 is the proposed designation for stainless steel conraining 17% chromium and 1% molybdenum. nickel additions were produced by induction melting in an argon atmosphere, using the split-heat technique. In this technique, the base composition is melted, and part of the melt is poured off to produce an ingot; then to the balance of the melt, the required alloying additions are made and the next ingot is cast. This process is repeated until a series of the desired compositions is cast. The 18% Cr-2% Mo ingots were hotforged, hot-rolled to 0.76-cm-thick strips, and coldrolled to 0.38-cm-thick strips. The 18% Cr-2% Mo alloys containing titanium were annealed for 1 hr at 104O~ the minimum temperature that prevented formation of a second phase in the high titanium alloy, and then water-quenched. The rest of the 18% Cr-2% Mo materials and the hot-rolled, commercial Types 430 and 434 steels were annealed at 815~ for 1 hr and water-quenched.
Comments: The electrodes for the potentiodynamic studies were mounted in acrylic plastic, the exposed surface (0.5 by 0.6 cm) always being a longitudinal section parallel to the rolled surface. Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization
Heat treatment: In this technique, the base composition is melted and part of the melt is cast into an ingot. To the balance of the melt, the required molybdenum addition is made and the next ingot is cast. This process is repeated until a series of the desired positions is cast. By this procedure, the residual and impurity elements, which were intended to be in the range commonly present in commercial stainless steels, were held essentially constant within each series. The ingots were hot-forged and hot-rolled to a thickness of 0.76 cm and then cold-rolled to 0.38 cm. The 13% nickel steels were annealed at 1120C for 1 hr and water-quenched. The 39% nickel steels and the high-purity alloys were annealed at 1150C for 1 hr and water-quenched.
Comments: test area 0.07 cm2; 0.3 um surface finish

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization
Heat treatment: All surfaces of the cast slabs were ground to remove imperfections and provide good rolling surfaces before annealing 16 hours at 1200C in argon atmosphere. The slabs were hot rolled at 1090C to 1/16 inch thickness. Oxide scale was subsequently removed by sand blasting before a final annealing treatment. Following preparation, each alloy was hot rolled to 0.1 inch sheet and water quenched. Hot rolling temperatures were restricted to a maximum of 982C and a minimum of 816C. The hot rolled sheet was electropolished in an aqueous 15wt% NaCl/ 30wt%H2SO4 electrolyte to remove surface scale and sheared into 1 inch wide strips running parallel to the hot rolling direction. The 1 inch wide hot rolled strips were subsequently cold rolled from 0.1 inch to a final thickness of 0.0625inch.

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization. The electrodes for the potentiodynamic studies were mounted in epoxy plastic with a single exposed surface parallel to the rolling plane. Electrical contact was made by soft-soldering a nickel wire to the back of the electrode. Contact between the solder or lead wire and the electrolyte was excluded by the plastic and glass tube. The 0.5 by 0.6 cm exposed surface was polished by using standard metallographic techniques, finishing with a distilled water slurry of 0.3 mu alumina. The edges of the electrode were masked with clear Glyptal varnish to prevent crevice corrosion. The coupons for the exposure tests, 2.5 by 2.5 by 0.3 cm, were surface ground and then polished through No. 600 wet silicon carbide paper. They were solvent degreased and rinsed in methanol before exposure.

Test Method:
Potentiodynamic Polarization - test electrodes were made from 0.25 mm wire looped to a diameter of
25 mm. Test solutions were prepared from reagent grade chemicals and
distilled water and the pH value was adjusted using H2SO4 or NaOH as required. The oxygen content of
the test solutions was reduced to a negligible value by bubbling nitrogen through them for a period of 24 h.
All electrochemical measurements were carried out in conventional setup, purged
with nitrogen during each experiment

Test Method:
The "scratch" technique was employed for the determination of pitting potentials.The electrode was first polarized potentiostatically to some potential well below the expected pitting potential.The polarization current was allowedto stabilize and then the electrode surface was scratched with a sharp silicon-carbide crystal mounted
on the end of a glass tube. The scratching of the electrode
surface resulted in a sharp polarization current
"blip." The electrode potential was manually adjusted
by 20 mV steps to more and more noble potential
values, until the scratch failed to repassivate, a failure
which was indicated by a gradual current rise after the
electrode was scratched. The pit was allowed to develop
for 10 min, and then the electrode was examined visually.
Only those results were considered to be valid
where pits actually developed at the scratched site.
Heat treatment: heat-treated for 1 hr at 1500F followed by water quenching
Microstructures:
Metallographic
examinations did not show the presence of
intermetallic phases in any of the materials.
Comments: polished only through 600-grit SiC metallographic paper.

Test Method:
To measure the pitting potentials, the potential was stepped upwards
by 25 mV every 400 s, beginning at -300 mV(SCE).
Heat treatment: annealed at 1200C for 24hr and water quenched
Comments:
Pitting potentials were measured in 1M KCI, using mechanically polished 0.4 cm2
coupons of the experimental alloys. To measure the pitting potentials, the potential was stepped upwards
by 25 mV every 400 s, beginning at -300 mV(SCE).

Test Method:
Potentiodynamic Polarization- Samples were mechanically polished with
emery paper up to grade 1000 under water, then degreased in absolute ethyl alcohol, washed in deionized water, and
dried by warm air blowing for electrochemical tests. Polarization curves were obtained potentiodynamically at a scan rate of 20 mV/min.
Heat treatment: Solution treatment was performed by heating in nitrogen at 1150 C for 30 minutes followed by water quenching
Comments:
Samples were mechanically polished with
emery paper up to grade 1000 under water, then degreased in absolute ethyl alcohol, washed in deionized water, and
dried by warm air blowing for electrochemical tests.

Test Solution: distilled water adjusted to pH 4(6.25 x 105 M H2SO4) containing 200 ppm Cl- (5.5 x 10-3 NaCl)
Test Method:
Potentiodynamic Polarization - the sample was stabilized in the electrolyte, which was sparged continuously with
oxygen (O2), until the potential change was < 1 mV/min, and this potential was considered as the OCP. Then, the sample was scanned potentiodynamically at a rate of 600 mV/h to a potential corresponding to a
current density of 103 A/cm2 and then scan direction was reversed.
Heat treatment: annealing in air for 1 h at 850 C (recrystallization) plus 7 days at 500C (ordering) followed by cooling in air,which produced the DO3 -ordered structure
Comments:
To prevent the initiation of crevice corrosion between the epoxy and specimen, the epoxy-specimen interface was painted with Amercoat 90 epoxy leaving an exposed area of 1 cm2 on the material surface. The painted sample was cured in an oven for 10 h at 70C. Just before introduction into the polarization cell, the exposed metal surface was polished by hand with cloth and a 9-microm diamond paste to remove the air-formed oxide film created during the epoxy curing process. The interface seal was abraded slightly but not damaged.
 Polarization tests were conducted in an aerated electrolyte.

 Polarization tests were conducted in an aerated electrolyte.

Test Solution: distilled water adjusted to pH 4(6.25 x 105 M H2SO4) containing 200 ppm Cl- (5.5 x 10-3 NaCl)
Test Method:
Potentiodynamic Polarization - the sample was stabilized in the electrolyte, which was sparged continuously with
oxygen (O2), until the potential change was < 1 mV/min, and this potential was considered as the OCP. Then, the sample was scanned potentiodynamically at a rate of 600 mV/h to a potential corresponding to a
current density of 103 A/cm2 and then scan direction was reversed.
Heat treatment: annealing in air for 1 h at 850 C (recrystallization) plus 7 days at 500C (ordering) followed by cooling in air,which produced the DO3 -ordered structure
Comments:
To prevent the initiation of crevice corrosion between the epoxy and specimen, the epoxy-specimen interface was painted with Amercoat 90 epoxy leaving an exposed area of 1 cm2 on the material surface. The painted sample was cured in an oven for 10 h at 70C. Just before introduction into the polarization cell, the exposed metal surface was polished by hand with cloth and a 9-microm diamond paste to remove the air-formed oxide film created during the epoxy curing process. The interface seal was abraded slightly but not damaged.
 Polarization tests were conducted in an aerated electrolyte.

Test Method: Potentiodynamic Polarization(Anodic polarization was applied to the working electrode after a stable corrosion potential had been achieved; this usually took about 2 h after immersion in the solution. As a measure of the resistance to pitting corrosion, the pitting potentials for the alloys were determined from the anodic polarization curve by the potential at which the anodic current density reached a value of 10 uA/cm2 after film breakdown.
Heat treatment:
The casts were homogenized for 2 h at
I250 C. and then hot-rolled into 5 mm thick plates. The specimen prepared by cold rolling the hot rolled plates into 2mm thick sheets and solution annealing for 20 min at 1050C, followed by water quenching
Comments:
The solutions were deaerated by purging with high-purity nitrogen 
throughout the test, starting from 1 h before the test.

Test Method: Potentiodynamic polarization. All studies were carried out with rotating disk electrodes of 0.1 cm2 (diameter 0.357 cm) insulated with a PTFE shrinkable tubing. Experiments were performed at 6000 rpm (in part at 600 rpm) in 1 M HCI at 25C under a nitrogen atmosphere.
Heat treatment: The binary Fe-Cr alloys were furnished by Climax Molybdenum. They were subsequently hot forged. The other alloys were prepared in our laboratory by alloying to the original Fe-Cr alloys the elements Mo, W, V or Si using a vacuum induction furnace under an argon atmosphere.
Microstructures: The metallographic examination revealed the presence of a few oxide inclusions in an otherwise apparently single phase ferritic matrix.
Comments: Pretreatment of the electrodes included grinding with emery papcr and polishing with alumina powder in water to 1/4 엸 finish. They were rinsed and cathodically polarized in the working electrolyte at -700 mV(SHE) for 10 min.

Test Method: Anodic Polarization -  Anodic polarization tests performed in deaerated 4 M sodium chloride (NaCl) solution at 80C. The electrochemical cell for the test consisted of a 1-L multineck flask, as specified in ASTM G 5 with a platinum counter electrode and a saturated calomel electrode (SCE) positioned in a salt bridge with a high-silica tip.
Heat treatment: solution-annealed for 2 h at 1,050C and then aged at 850C for 30 min, 1 h, and 10 h.

Potentiostatic Polarization

Potentiostatic Polarization. For most of the measurements, Al electrodes were employed measuring 1.5 cm long and 0.4 cm in diameter. One end of each electrode was drilled and tapped, allowing a threaded member attached to a nickel wire to hold the electrode firmly against a glass tube separated by a water-tight Teflon gasket. Only the electrode surface, totally immersed, Teflon, and glass made contact with the electrolyte. Specimens were polished to 3/0 emery paper followed by pickling in 2N NaOH at 80~ for 5 min and then washing in distilled water.
